# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: metro-ethernet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] It has become dominant in enterprise networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] This dominance has led to high production-volume components, which in turn have allowed extremely low cost per bit.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Likewise, Ethernet has a long history of re-inventing itself.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] From the original copper coaxial cable format ("thicknet") it has extended its scope to nearly all copper, optical fiber and wireless physical media.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Bit rates have continued to increase, traditionally growing tenfold each time a new rate is defined.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Gigabit Ethernet interfaces are widely deployed in PCs and servers, and 10 Gbit/s in local area network (LAN) backbones.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Rates up to 100 Gigabit Ethernet were standardized in 2010 and 2011.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Ethernet's dominance is partly attributed to the simple advantages for the industry of adopting a single standard to drive up volumes and drive down prices.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] In part, it is also due to ease of deployment, using its ability to self-configure based on the key concepts of *learning bridge* (flooding, and associating learned destination addresses with bridge ports) and Spanning Tree Protocol (the protocol used for avoiding bridging loops).
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Historically, competing protocols and cabling have been created in order to access higher speed devices than contemporary Ethernet-connected devices handled at an affordable price.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Examples include FireWire and Light Peak.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] One motive to create competing standards has been to drive down the price of comparable-speed Ethernet devices.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Once this purpose is achieved, competing standards tend to disappear or be confined to very specialized niches.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Ethernet is a fairly simple protocol which has scaled to hundreds of thousands of times faster speeds and consistently been able to adapt to meet the needs and demands of new markets.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] For example, time domain capabilities are being added to IEEE 802.3 Ethernet to support IEEE 802.1 Audio Video Bridging (AVB), and these capabilities will be applicable to time sensitive carrier applications likewise IEEE 1588.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Customer LAN networks are increasingly connected to wide-area telecommunications networks over Ethernet interfaces or to devices that bridge digital subscriber line (DSL) or wireless to these.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Moreover, customers are familiar with the capabilities of Ethernet networks, and would like to extend these capabilities to multi-site networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Meanwhile, the needs of such networks have expanded to include many services previously handled only on the LAN or by specialized connections, notably video and backup.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] It is not practical to expand most small networks beyond 1G or at most 2G (dual teaming gigabit) capacity per segment, since the bottleneck remains in the wide area links to other offices and online services.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] They are also constrained as services cannot be migrated from local to wide area services too fast lest they exceed the total provisioning available and result in unacceptable quality.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Services that try to expand too fast lose money while those that wait too long lose customers.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Accordingly, carriers must expand their services conservatively and pay close attention to quality of service (QoS).
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The MEF was formed in 2001 in order to develop ubiquitous business services for Enterprise users principally accessed over optical metropolitan networks in order to connect their Enterprise LANs.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The principal concept was to bring the simplicity and cost model of Ethernet to the wide area network.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] To create a market in Ethernet services, it is necessary to clarify and standardise the services to be provided.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Recognising this, the industry created the MEF.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] All these services provide standard definitions of such characteristics as bandwidth, resilience and service multiplexing, allowing customers to compare service offerings and facilitating service level agreements (SLAs).
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The services are categorized as an E-line service type, with an expectation of low frame delay, frame delay variation and frame loss ratio.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] EPL is implemented using a point-to-point EVC with no service multiplexing at each UNI (physical interface), i.e., all service frames at the UNI are mapped to a single EVC (a.k.a. all-to-one bundling).
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Due to a high degree of transparency, EPL is often used to provide point-to-point transparent LAN service (TLS), where the service frame's header and payload are identical at both the source and destination UNI.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Some implementations tunnel most Ethernet Layer 2 control protocols (L2CPs) except for some link-layer L2CPs such as IEEE 802.3x pause frames.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Unlike EPL, EVPL allows for service multiplexing, i.e., multiple EVCs or Ethernet services per UNI.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The other difference between the EVPL and EPL is the degree of transparency: while EPL is highly transparent, filtering only the pause frames, EVPL is required to either peer or drop most of the Layer 2 control protocols.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The MEF does not specify how Ethernet services are to be provided in a carrier network.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Despite the advantages described above, Ethernet has traditionally had a number of limitations in the WAN application.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The "bridge" and "spanning tree" concepts described above do not scale to large international networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Moreover, Ethernet has lacked some of the dependability features necessary in this application (in particular, mechanisms to isolate one customer's traffic from another, to measure performance of a customer service instance, and to rapidly detect and repair failures in large networks).
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Because of these limitations, and because of the need to make use of pre-existing equipment, Ethernet services have been carried across wide area networks using other technologies.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Two types of technology have been widely used, while a third (Carrier-Ethernet transport) is rapidly emerging as a viable and logical option for Carrier-Ethernet services.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Ethernet services are carried over IP/MPLS networks making use of a wide range of IP-related protocols.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Ethernet links are transported as "pseudowires" using MPLS label-switched paths (LSPs) inside an outer MPLS "tunnel".
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] This strategy can support both point-to-point (Virtual Private Wire Service - VPWS) and multipoint (Virtual Private LAN service - VPLS) services, and has recently achieved significant deployment in routed networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] It makes use of a number of basic transport protocols, including SDH and (increasingly) Ethernet.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Proponents of Carrier-Class Ethernet argue Ethernet is the best for Metro Area Networks because all data traffic originates as Ethernet.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Ethernet's ubiquitous presence in the LANs worldwide drives down the cost of Ethernet as a technology.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Thus, the use of Ethernet in a metro network allows service providers to take advantage of volumes that a much larger enterprise segment commands.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Carrier-Ethernet Transport (CET) usually involves an evolution of conventional Ethernet and comprises multiple technology components.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Provider Backbone Bridges (PBB) provides the scalability and a secure demarcation, while Provider Backbone Bridge Traffic Engineering (PBB-TE, commonly called PBT) provides for traffic-engineering and an effective transport for protected Ethernet services.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Connectivity-Fault Management (CFM-OAM) provides the much-required OAM that makes Ethernet carrier grade.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Carrier Ethernet demarcation is a key element in Carrier Ethernet services and transport networks for business, wholesale and mobile backhaul applications, as it enables service providers to extend their control over the entire service path, starting from the hand off points.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] This is achieved by connecting customer premises equipment (CPE) to the network with provider-owned demarcation devices that are deployed at customer locations, thereby enabling a clear separation between the user and provider networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Carrier Ethernet demarcation devices (EDD) are required to support services, such as Ethernet Private Line (EPL), Ethernet Virtual Private Line (EVPL or E-LAN), and Ethernet Virtual Private Tree (E-Tree), as specified by the MEF.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Such support needs to include service level agreement (SLA) management capabilities, with consistent performance over fiber, DSL, bonded PDH, and SDH/SONET access lines.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The industry has made a concerted effort to resolve the limitations of Ethernet in the WAN described above, so as to allow the use of "native" Ethernet technologies by network providers.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The key roles have been played by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) 802.1 and 802.3 standards committees.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] IEEE 802.1 has addressed the scalability and management issues in the standards for Provider Bridges (802.1ad) and Provider Backbone Bridges (802.1ah).
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] These standards allow for Ethernet networks of planetary scale.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] Associated standards (IEEE 802.1ag, and related ITU-T standard Y.1731) provide Operations and Maintenance (OAM) capabilities allowing connectivity verification, rapid recovery, and performance measurement.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The IEEE 802.3 Working Group in close cooperation with the ITU have been working to simplify the transport of 40G and 100G technologies being developed by both bodies: 802.3 for LAN and ITU for the OTN.
[src:metro-ethernet/carrier-ethernet] The OIF and the Ethernet Alliance have also been working cooperatively with their members to enable future enhancements to Ethernet for the WAN while looking to the future speed of Ethernet technologies and services.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] A working group of the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) produced the standards known as **IEEE 802.3ah-2004**, which were later included in the overall standard IEEE 802.3-2008.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] EFM is often used in active optical network deployments.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] Although it is often used for businesses, it can also be known as **Ethernet to the home** (**ETTH**).
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] One family of standards known as **Ethernet passive optical network** (**EPON**) uses a passive optical network.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] With wide, metro, and local area networks using various forms of Ethernet, the goal was to eliminate non-native transport such as Ethernet over Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) from access networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] One early effort was the EtherLoop technology invented at Nortel Networks in 1996, and then spun off into the company Elastic Networks in 1998.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] The hope was to combine the packet-based nature of Ethernet with the ability of digital subscriber line (DSL) technology to work over existing telephone access wires.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] The name comes from local loop, which traditionally describes the wires from a telephone company office to a subscriber.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] The protocol was half-duplex with control from the provider side of the loop.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] It adapted to line conditions with a peak of 10 Mbit/s advertised, but 4-6 Mbit/s more typical, at a distance of about 12,000 feet (3,700 m).
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] Symbol rates were 1 megabaud or 1.67 megabaud, with 2, 4, or 6 bits per symbol.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] The EtherLoop product name was registered as a trademark in the US and Canada.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] The EtherLoop technology was eventually purchased by Paradyne Networks in 2002, which was in turn purchased by Zhone Technologies in 2005.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] Another effort was the concept promoted by Michael Silverton of using Ethernet variants that used fiber-optic communication to residential as well as business customers.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] This was an example of what has become known as fiber to the home (FTTH).
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] The Fiberhood Networks company provided this service from 1999 to 2001.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] Some early products around the year 2000, were marketed as 10BaseS by Infineon Technologies, although they did not technically use baseband signalling, but rather passband as in very-high-bit-rate digital subscriber line (VDSL) technology.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] A patent was filed in 1997 by Peleg Shimon, Porat Boaz, Noam Alroy, Rubinstain Avinoam and Sfadya Yackow.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] Long Reach Ethernet was the product name used by Cisco Systems starting in 2001.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] It supported modes of 5 Mbit/s, 10 Mbit/s, and 15 Mbit/s depending on distance.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] In October 2000 Howard Frazier issued a call for interest on "Ethernet in the Last Mile".
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] At the November 2000 meeting, IEEE 802.3 created the "Ethernet in the First Mile" study group, and on July 16, 2001, the 802.3ah working group.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] In parallel participating vendors formed the Ethernet in the First Mile Alliance (EFMA) in December 2001 to promote Ethernet subscriber access technology and support the IEEE standard efforts.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] At an early meeting, the EtherLoop technology was called 100BASE-CU and another technology called EoVDSL for Ethernet over VDSL.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] The working group's EFM standard was approved on June 24, 2004, and published on September 7, 2004, as IEEE 802.3ah-2004.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] In 2005, it was included into the base IEEE 802.3 standard.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] In 2005, the EFMA was absorbed by the Metro Ethernet Forum.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] In early 2006, work began on an even higher-speed 10 gigabit/second Ethernet passive optical network (10G-EPON) standard, ratified in 2009 as IEEE 802.3av.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] The work on the EPON was continued by the IEEE P802.3bk *Extended EPON* Task Force, formed in March 2012.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] The major goals for this Task Force included adding support for PX30, PX40, PRX40, and PR40 power budget classes to both 1G-EPON and 10G-EPON.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] The 802.3bk amendment was approved by the IEEE-SA SB in August 2013 and published soon thereafter as the standard IEEE Std 802.3bk-2013.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] In November 2011, IEEE 802.3 began work on EPON Protocol over Coax (EPoC).
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] On June 4, 2020, the IEEE approved IEEE 802.3ca which allows for symmetric or asymmetric operation with downstream speeds of 25 Gbit/s or 50 Gbit/s, and upstream speeds of 10 Gbit/s, 25 Gbit/s, or 50 Gbit/s over passive optical networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] EFM also addresses other issues, required for mass deployment of Ethernet services, such as operations, administration, and management (OA&M) and compatibility with existing technologies (such as plain old telephone service spectral compatibility for copper twisted pair).
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] Fiber to the home can use a passive optical network.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] Additionally Clause 57 (802.3ah-2004) defines link-level OAM, including discovery, link monitoring, remote fault indication, loopbacks, and variable access.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] 2BASE-TL PHYs deliver a minimum of 2 Mbit/s over distances of up to 2.7 kilometres (8,900 ft), using ITU-T G.991.2 (G.SHDSL.bis) technology over a single copper pair.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] These PHYs may also support an optional aggregation or bonding of multiple copper pairs, called PME Aggregation Function (PAF).
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] For a single pair, the minimum possible link bitrate is 192 kbit/s (3 x 64 kbit/s) and the maximum bitrate is 5.7 Mbit/s (89 x 64 kbit/s).
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] On a 0.5 mm wire with 3 dB noise margin and no spectral limitations, the max bitrate can be achieved over distances of up to 1 kilometre (3,300 ft).
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] At 6 kilometres (20,000 ft) the maximum achievable bitrate is about 850 kbit/s.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] The throughput of a 2BASE-TL link is lower than the link's bitrate by an average 5%, due to 64/65-octet encoding and PAF overhead; both factors depend on packet size.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] 10PASS-TS PHYs deliver a minimum of 10 Mbit/s over distances of up to 750 metres (2,460 ft), using ITU-T G.993.1 (VDSL) technology over a single copper pair.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] VDSL is a short range technology designed to provide broadband over distances less than 1 km of voice-grade copper twisted pair line, but connection data rates deteriorate quickly as the line distance increases.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] This has led to VDSL being referred to as a "fiber to the curb" technology, because it requires fiber backhaul to connect with a carrier network over greater distances.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] VDSL Ethernet in the first mile services using may be a useful way to standardise functionality on metro Ethernet networks, or potentially to distribute internet access services over voice-grade wiring in multi-dwelling unit buildings.
[src:metro-ethernet/ethernet-in-the-first-mile] However, VDSL2 has already proven to be a versatile and faster standard with greater reach than VDSL.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] A **metropolitan-area Ethernet**, **Ethernet MAN**, **carrier Ethernet** or **metro Ethernet** network is a metropolitan area network (MAN) that is based on Ethernet standards.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] It is commonly used to connect subscribers to a larger service network or for internet access.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] Businesses can also use metropolitan-area Ethernet to connect their own offices to each other.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] An Ethernet interface is typically more economical than a synchronous digital hierarchy (SONET/SDH) or plesiochronous digital hierarchy (PDH) interface of the same bandwidth.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] Another distinct advantage of an Ethernet-based access network is that it can be easily connected to the customer network, due to the prevalent use of Ethernet in corporate and residential networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] A typical service provider's network is a collection of switches and routers connected through optical fiber.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] The topology could be a ring, hub-and-spoke (star), or full or partial mesh.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] The network will also have a hierarchy: core, distribution (aggregation), and access.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] The core in most cases is an existing IP/MPLS backbone but may migrate to newer forms of Ethernet transport in the form of 10 Gbit/s, 40 Gbit/s, or 100 Gbit/s speeds or even possibly 400 Gbit/s to Terabit Ethernet network in the future.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] Ethernet on the MAN can be used as pure Ethernet, Ethernet over SDH, Ethernet over Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS), or Ethernet over DWDM.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] Ethernet-based deployments with no other underlying transport are cheaper but are harder to implement in a resilient and scalable manner, which has limited its use to small-scale or experimental deployments.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] SDH-based deployments are useful when there is an existing SDH infrastructure already in place; its main shortcoming is the loss of flexibility in bandwidth management due to the rigid hierarchy imposed by the SDH network.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] MPLS-based deployments are costly but highly reliable and scalable and are typically used by large service providers.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] Familiar network domains are likely to exist regardless of the transport technology chosen to implement metropolitan area networks: Access, aggregation/distribution, and core.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] Much of the functionality of Ethernet MANs such as virtual private lines or virtual private networks is implemented by the use of Ethernet VLAN tags that allow differentiation of each part of the network.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] Logical differentiation of the physical network helps to identify the rights that the traffic has and to ease the management of hosts' access rights with respect to other users and networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] A Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) metro Ethernet network uses MPLS in the service provider's network.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] The subscriber will get an Ethernet interface on copper (for example, 100BASE-TX) or fiber (such as 100BASE-FX).
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] The customer's Ethernet packet is transported over MPLS and the service provider network uses Ethernet again as the underlying technology to transport MPLS.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] So, it is Ethernet over MPLS over Ethernet.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] Label Distribution Protocol (LDP) signaling can be used as site to site signaling for the inner label (VC label) and Resource reSerVation Protocol-Traffic Engineering (RSVP-TE) or LDP may be used as Network signaling for the outer label.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] One restoration mechanism used in an MPLS based Metro Ethernet Networks is Fast ReRoute (FRR) to achieve sub-50ms convergence of MPLS local protection.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] For each deployment situation the benefit versus cost of MPLS must be weighed carefully, so if not implemented on a carrier's distribution network there might be more benefit for MPLS the core network.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] In some situations the cost may not warrant the benefits, particularly if sub 50ms convergence time is already being achieved with pure Ethernet.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] In a properly designed Ethernet VLAN network, each switched path can have 4094 single tag VLANs.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] VLAN stacking, so with such aggregation devices properly placed in the center of a network, end segments and rings of single tag devices can receive only the traffic that they need.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] When using MPLS, Ethernet VLANs have local meaning only (like Frame Relay PVC).
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] Same scalability considerations apply to the MAC addresses where in a pure Layer 2 Ethernet MAN all MAC addresses are being shared across the network, although this issue can be managed by smart network design and choosing switches with MAC tables sufficient for the size of network segments.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] (30 to sub 50 ms convergence depending on network design) while MPLS-based MANs use mechanisms such as MPLS Fast Reroute to achieve SDH-like (50 ms) convergence times.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] where appropriate to add link redundancy and recovery in distribution networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] Some Ethernet vendors' RSTP convergence is also sub-50 ms, but this convergence time may vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] VLL, FR VLL, etc.) an MPLS-based Metro Ethernet can backhaul IP/Ethernet traffic together with virtually any type of traffic coming from customer or other access networks (i.e.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] ATM aggregation for UMTS or TDM aggregation for GSM), while this could be more challenging in a pure Ethernet scenario.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] MPLS-based MAN offers a wide set of troubleshooting and OAM MPLS-based tools which enrich Service Providers ability to effectively troubleshoot and diagnose network problems.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] These include for example, MAC ping, MAC traceroute, LSP ping etc.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] for monitoring and troubleshooting Ethernet networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] Some service providers deployed metro Ethernet networks using fixed wireless technology.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] These networks commonly are engineered with a majority of the network traffic using a mesh of multi-point and point-to-point microwave links.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] Carriers have more recently been referred to as metro wireless in many cases.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] Metro Wireless providers in many cases are able to produce shorter installation times due to less permitting and procedure necessary.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] Many consumers now rely on this type of technology to allow Internet access in areas where local telephone companies and cable companies do not or will no longer service due to copper theft or other business reasons.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] Wireless is also commonly used as a true redundant path to the Internet.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] In late September 2007 Verizon Business announced metro Ethernet across Asia-Pacific including Australia, Singapore, Japan and Hong Kong using Nortel equipment.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] In late January 2009, Windstream announced it would begin offering metro Ethernet service to small and medium business customers.
[src:metro-ethernet/metro-ethernet] In May 2011, Comcast announced its own metro Ethernet services to business customers in the United States.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] The now-ubiquitous Ethernet was initially defined as a local area network (LAN) technology to interconnect the computers within a small organization in which these host computers were very close in proximity to each other.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] Over the years, Ethernet has become such a popular technology that it became the default Data Link Layer (OSI Layer 2) mechanism for data transport.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] This created a need for extending the Ethernet from a customer LAN bridging domain to service provider MAN, also known as the Provider bridging domain.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] For this, a 4 byte S-Tag or Service Tag, a type of Virtual LAN tag, was added to the header of the Ethernet frame in IEEE 802.1ad standard.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] In the service provider domain, switching was based on S-Tag and destination MAC address, and C-tag was used to create virtual LAN within the customer domain.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] This technology is also known as QinQ or Q-tunneling.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] QinQ does not offer true separation of customer and provider domains but is merely a way to overcome the limitations on the VLAN identifier space.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] It can also help in separation of the customer and provider control domains when used with other features like control protocol tunneling or Per-VLAN Spanning Tree etc.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] There is still the problem of having too little control on the MAC addresses, since QinQ forwarding is still based on the customer destination addresses.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] The idea of PBB is to offer complete separation of customer and provider domains.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] For this purpose, a new Ethernet header has been defined.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] An IPv4 packet, containing TCP with HTTPS, for example.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] 0x88A8 indicates Service VLAN tag identifier (S-Tag).
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] 0x887E indicates Provider Backbone Bridges.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] The bridges in the PBB domain switch based on the B-VID and B-DA values, which contain 60 bits total.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] Bridges learn based on the B-SA and ingress port value and hence is completely unaware of the customer MAC addresses.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] I-SID allows distinguishing the services within a PBB domain.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] PBB is the foundation for the IEEE 802.1Qay PBB-TE standard, which was standardized in 2009.
[src:metro-ethernet/provider-backbone-bridges] PBB is sometimes referred to as MAC-in-MAC.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] In the field of computer networking and other packet-switched telecommunication networks, quality of service refers to traffic prioritization and resource reservation control mechanisms rather than the achieved service quality.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Quality of service is the ability to provide different priorities to different applications, users, or data flows, or to guarantee a certain level of performance to a data flow.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Quality of service is particularly important for the transport of traffic with special requirements, including voice over IP and other audio networking techniques, professional video over IP, card-based payments, and real-time computing.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] In the field of telephony, quality of service was defined by the ITU in 1994.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Quality of service comprises requirements on all the aspects of a connection, such as service response time, loss, signal-to-noise ratio, crosstalk, echo, interrupts, frequency response, loudness levels, and so on.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] A subset of telephony QoS is grade of service (GoS) requirements, which comprises aspects of a connection relating to capacity and coverage of a network, for example, guaranteed maximum blocking probability and outage probability.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] In the field of computer networking and other packet-switched telecommunication networks, teletraffic engineering refers to traffic prioritization and resource reservation control mechanisms rather than the achieved service quality.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] For example, a required bit rate, delay, delay variation, packet loss or bit error rates may be guaranteed.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Quality of service is important for real-time streaming multimedia applications such as voice over IP, multiplayer online games and IPTV, since these often require a fixed bit rate and are delay sensitive.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Quality of service is especially important in networks where the capacity is a limited resource, for example, in cellular data communication.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] A network or protocol that supports QoS may agree on a traffic contract with the application software and reserve capacity in the network nodes, for example during a session establishment phase.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] During the session, it may monitor the achieved level of performance, for example, the data rate and delay, and dynamically control scheduling priorities in the network nodes.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] It may release the reserved capacity during a tear down phase.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] A best-effort network or service does not support quality of service.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] An alternative to complex QoS control mechanisms is to provide high-quality communication over a best-effort network by over-provisioning the capacity so that it is sufficient for the expected peak traffic load.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] The resulting absence of network congestion reduces or eliminates the need for QoS mechanisms.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] QoS is sometimes used as a quality measure, with many alternative definitions, rather than referring to the ability to reserve resources.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Quality of service sometimes refers to the level of quality of service, i.e. the guaranteed service quality.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] High QoS is often confused with a high level of performance, for example high bit rate, low latency and low bit error rate.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] QoS is sometimes used in application layer services such as telephony and streaming video to describe a metric that reflects or predicts the subjectively experienced quality.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] In this context, QoS is the acceptable cumulative effect on subscriber satisfaction of all imperfections affecting the service.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Other terms with similar meaning are the quality of experience (QoE), mean opinion score (MOS), perceptual speech quality measure (PSQM) and perceptual evaluation of video quality (PEVQ).
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] A number of attempts for layer 2 technologies that add QoS tags to the data have gained popularity in the past.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Examples are Frame Relay, Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) and Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) (a technique between layer 2 and 3).
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Despite these network technologies remaining in use today, this kind of network lost attention after the advent of Ethernet networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Today, Ethernet is, by far, the most popular layer 2 technology.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Conventional Internet routers and network switches operate on a best-effort basis.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] This equipment is less expensive, less complex and faster and thus more popular than earlier, more complex technologies that provide QoS mechanisms.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Ethernet optionally uses 802.1p to signal the priority of a frame.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] There were four *type of service* bits and three *precedence* bits originally provided in each IP packet header, but they were not generally respected.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] These bits were later re-defined as Differentiated services code points (DSCP).
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] With the advent of IPTV and IP telephony, QoS mechanisms are increasingly available to the end user.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] In packet-switched networks, quality of service is affected by various factors, which can be divided into human and technical factors.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Human factors include: stability of service quality, availability of service, waiting times and user information.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Technical factors include: reliability, scalability, effectiveness, maintainability and network congestion.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Due to varying load from disparate users sharing the same network resources, the maximum throughput that can be provided to a certain data stream may be too low for real-time multimedia services.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] The network may fail to deliver (*drop*) some packets due to network congestion.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] The receiving application may ask for this information to be retransmitted, possibly resulting in congestive collapse or unacceptable delays in the overall transmission.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Sometimes packets are corrupted due to bit errors caused by noise and interference, especially in wireless communications and long copper wires.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] The receiver has to detect this, and, just as if the packet was dropped, may ask for this information to be retransmitted.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] It might take a long time for each packet to reach its destination because it gets held up in long queues, or it takes a less direct route to avoid congestion.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] In some cases, excessive latency can render an application such as VoIP or online gaming unusable.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Packets from the source will reach the destination with different delays.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] A packet's delay varies with its position in the queues of the routers along the path between source and destination, and this position can vary unpredictably.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Delay variation can be absorbed at the receiver, but in so doing increases the overall latency for the stream.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] When a collection of related packets is routed through a network, different packets may take different routes, each resulting in a different delay.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] The result is that the packets arrive in a different order than they were sent.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] This problem requires special additional protocols for rearranging out-of-order packets.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] The reordering process requires additional buffering at the receiver, and, as with packet delay variation, increases the overall latency for the stream.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] These types of service are called *inelastic*, meaning that they require a certain minimum bit rate and a certain maximum latency to function.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] By contrast, *elastic* applications can take advantage of however much or little bandwidth is available.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Bulk file transfer applications that rely on TCP are generally elastic.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Circuit-switched networks, especially those intended for voice transmission, such as ATM or GSM, have QoS in the core protocol; resources are reserved at each step on the network for the call as it is set up, and there is no need for additional procedures to achieve the required performance.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Shorter data units and built-in QoS were some of the unique selling points of ATM for applications such as video on demand.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] An alternative to complex QoS control mechanisms is to provide high-quality communication by generously over-provisioning a network so that capacity is based on peak traffic load estimates.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] This approach is simple for networks with predictable peak loads.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] This calculation may need to appreciate demanding applications that can compensate for variations in bandwidth and delay with large receive buffers, which is often possible, for example, in video streaming.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Over-provisioning can be of limited use in the face of transport protocols (such as TCP) that, over time, increase the amount of data placed on the network until all available bandwidth is consumed and packets are dropped.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Such greedy protocols tend to increase latency and packet loss for all users.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] The amount of over-provisioning in interior links required to replace QoS depends on the number of users and their traffic demands.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] This limits the usability of over-provisioning.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Newer, more bandwidth-intensive applications and the addition of more users result in the loss of over-provisioned networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] This then requires a physical update of the relevant network links, which is an expensive process.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Thus, over-provisioning cannot be blindly assumed on the Internet.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Commercial VoIP services are often competitive with traditional telephone service in terms of call quality, even without QoS mechanisms in use on the user's connection to their ISP and the VoIP provider's connection to a different ISP.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Under high load conditions, however, VoIP may degrade to cell-phone quality or worse.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] The mathematics of packet traffic indicates that the network requires just 60% more raw capacity under conservative assumptions.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Unlike single-owner networks, the Internet is a series of exchange points interconnecting private networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Hence the Internet's core is owned and managed by a number of different network service providers, not a single entity.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Its behavior is much more unpredictable.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] There are two principal approaches to QoS in modern packet-switched IP networks: a parameterized system based on an exchange of application requirements with the network, and a prioritized system where each packet identifies a desired service level to the network.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Early work used the integrated services (IntServ) philosophy of reserving network resources.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] In this model, applications used RSVP to request and reserve resources through a network.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] While IntServ mechanisms do work, it was realized that in a broadband network typical of a larger service provider, Core routers would be required to accept, maintain, and tear down thousands or possibly tens of thousands of reservations.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] It was believed that this approach would not scale with the growth of the Internet, and in any event was antithetical to the end-to-end principle, the notion of designing networks so that core routers do little more than simply switch packets at the highest possible rates.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Under DiffServ, packets are marked either by the traffic sources themselves or by the edge devices where the traffic enters the network.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] In response to these markings, routers and switches use various queuing strategies to tailor performance to requirements.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] At the IP layer, DSCP markings use the 6-bit DS field in the IP packet header.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] At the MAC layer, VLAN IEEE 802.1Q can be used to carry 3 bits of essentially the same information.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Routers and switches supporting DiffServ configure their network scheduler to use multiple queues for packets awaiting transmission from bandwidth-constrained (e.g., wide area) interfaces.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Router vendors provide different capabilities for configuring this behavior, including the number of queues supported, the relative priorities of queues, and the bandwidth reserved for each queue.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] In practice, when a packet must be forwarded from an interface with queuing, packets requiring low jitter (e.g., VoIP or videoconferencing) are given priority over packets in other queues.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Typically, some bandwidth is allocated by default to network control packets (such as Internet Control Message Protocol and routing protocols), while best-effort traffic might simply be given whatever bandwidth is left over.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] At the medium access control (MAC) layer, VLAN IEEE 802.1Q and IEEE 802.1p can be used to distinguish between Ethernet frames and classify them.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Queueing theory models have been developed on performance analysis and QoS for MAC layer protocols.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Cisco IOS NetFlow and the Cisco Class Based QoS (CBQoS) Management Information Base (MIB) are marketed by Cisco Systems.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] One compelling example of the need for QoS on the Internet relates to congestive collapse.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] The Internet relies on congestion avoidance protocols, primarily as built into Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), to reduce traffic under conditions that would otherwise lead to congestive collapse.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] QoS applications, such as VoIP and IPTV, require largely constant bitrates and low latency, therefore they cannot use TCP and cannot otherwise reduce their traffic rate to help prevent congestion.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Service-level agreements limit traffic that can be offered to the Internet and thereby enforce traffic shaping that can prevent it from becoming overloaded, and are hence an indispensable part of the Internet's ability to handle a mix of real-time and non-real-time traffic without collapse.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Several QoS mechanisms and schemes exist for IP networking.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] QoS capabilities are available in the following network technologies.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] End-to-end quality of service can require a method of coordinating resource allocation between one autonomous system and another.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) defined the Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) for bandwidth reservation as a proposed standard in 1997.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] RSVP is an end-to-end bandwidth reservation and admission control protocol.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] RSVP was not widely adopted due to scalability limitations.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] The more scalable traffic engineering version, RSVP-TE, is used in many networks to establish traffic-engineered Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) label-switched paths.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] The IETF also defined Next Steps in Signaling (NSIS) with QoS signalling as a target.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] NSIS is a development and simplification of RSVP.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Research consortia such as "end-to-end quality of service support over heterogeneous networks" (EuQoS, from 2004 through 2007) and fora such as the IPsphere Forum developed more mechanisms for handshaking QoS invocation from one domain to the next.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] IPsphere defined the Service Structuring Stratum (SSS) signaling bus in order to establish, invoke and (attempt to) assure network services.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] EuQoS conducted experiments to integrate Session Initiation Protocol, Next Steps in Signaling and IPsphere's SSS with an estimated cost of about 15.6 million Euro and published a book.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] A research project Multi Service Access Everywhere (MUSE) defined another QoS concept in a first phase from January 2004 through February 2006, and a second phase from January 2006 through 2007.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Another research project named PlaNetS was proposed for European funding circa 2005.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] A broader European project called "Architecture and design for the future Internet" known as 4WARD had a budget estimated at 23.4 million Euro and was funded from January 2008 through June 2010.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] It included a "Quality of Service Theme" and published a book.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Another European project, called WIDENS (Wireless Deployable Network System), proposed a bandwidth reservation approach for mobile wireless multirate adhoc networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Strong cryptography network protocols such as Secure Sockets Layer, I2P, and virtual private networks obscure the data transferred using them.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] As all electronic commerce on the Internet requires the use of such strong cryptography protocols, unilaterally downgrading the performance of encrypted traffic creates an unacceptable hazard for customers.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Yet, encrypted traffic is otherwise unable to undergo deep packet inspection for QoS.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Protocols like ICA and RDP may encapsulate other traffic (e.g. printing, video streaming) with varying requirements that can make optimization difficult.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] The Internet2 project found, in 2001, that the QoS protocols were probably not deployable inside its Abilene Network with equipment available at that time.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] The group predicted that "logistical, financial, and organizational barriers will block the way toward any bandwidth guarantees" by protocol modifications aimed at QoS.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] They believed that the economics would encourage network providers to deliberately erode the quality of best effort traffic as a way to push customers to higher-priced QoS services.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Instead, they proposed over-provisioning of capacity as more cost-effective at the time.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] The Abilene network study was the basis for the testimony of Gary Bachula to the US Senate Commerce Committee's hearing on Network Neutrality in early 2006.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] He expressed the opinion that adding more bandwidth was more effective than any of the various schemes for accomplishing QoS they examined.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Bachula's testimony has been cited by proponents of a law banning quality of service as proof that no legitimate purpose is served by such an offering.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] This argument is dependent on the assumption that over-provisioning isn't a form of QoS and that it is always possible.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Cost and other factors affect the ability of carriers to build and maintain permanently over-provisioned networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Mobile cellular service providers may offer mobile QoS to customers just as the wired public switched telephone network service providers and Internet service providers may offer QoS.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] QoS mechanisms are always provided for circuit switched services, and are essential for inelastic services, for example streaming multimedia.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Mobility adds complications to QoS mechanisms.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] A phone call or other session may be interrupted after a handover if the new base station is overloaded.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Unpredictable handovers make it impossible to give an absolute QoS guarantee during the session initiation phase.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Quality of service in the field of telephony was first defined in 1994 in ITU-T Recommendation E.800.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] This definition is very broad, listing 6 primary components: Support, Operability, Accessibility, Retainability, Integrity and Security.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] In 1998 the ITU published a document discussing QoS in the field of data networking.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] X.641 offers a means of developing or enhancing standards related to QoS and provides concepts and terminology that should assist in maintaining the consistency of related standards.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] Some QoS-related IETF Request for Comments (RFC)s are *Baker, Fred; Black, David L.; Nichols, Kathleen; Blake, Steven L.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] (December 1998), *Definition of the Differentiated services Field (DS Field) in the IPv4 and IPv6 Headers*, doi:10.17487/RFC2474, RFC 2474*, and *Braden, Robert T.; Zhang, Lixia; Berson, Steven; Herzog, Shai; Jamin, Sugih (September 1997), Braden, R.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] (ed.), *Resource ReSerVation Protocol (RSVP)*, doi:10.17487/RFC2205, RFC 2205*; both these are discussed above.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] The IETF has also published two RFCs giving background on QoS: *Huston, Geoff (November 2000), *Next Steps for the IP QoS Architecture*, doi:10.17487/RFC2990, RFC 2990*, and *Floyd, S.; Kempf, J.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] (ed.), *IAB Concerns Regarding Congestion Control for Voice Traffic in the Internet*, doi:10.17487/RFC3714, RFC 3714*.
[src:metro-ethernet/quality-of-service] The document tries to identify applications commonly run over an IP network, groups them into traffic classes, studies the treatment required by these classes from the network, and suggests which of the QoS mechanisms commonly available in routers can be used to implement those treatments.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] A **wide area network** (**WAN**) is a telecommunications network that extends over a large geographic area.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Wide area networks are often established with leased telecommunication circuits.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Businesses, as well as schools and government entities, use wide area networks to relay data to staff, students, clients, buyers and suppliers from various locations around the world.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] In essence, this mode of telecommunication allows a business to effectively carry out its daily functions regardless of location.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Many WANs are, however, built for one particular organization and are private.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] WANs can be separated from local area networks (LANs) in that the latter refers to physically proximal networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] The textbook definition of a WAN is a computer network spanning regions, countries, or even the world.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] However, in terms of the application of communication protocols and concepts, it may be best to view WANs as computer networking technologies used to transmit data over long distances, and between different networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] WANs are used to connect LANs and other types of networks together so that users and computers in one location can communicate with users and computers in other locations.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Many WANs are built for one particular organization and are private.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Others, built by Internet service providers, provide connections from an organization's LAN to the Internet.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] WANs are often built using leased lines.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] At each end of the leased line, a router connects the LAN on one side with a second router within the LAN on the other.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Because leased lines can be very expensive, instead of using leased lines, WANs can also be built using less costly circuit switching or packet switching methods.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Network protocols, including TCP/IP, deliver transport and addressing functions.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Protocols including Packet over SONET/SDH, Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS), Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) and Frame Relay are often used by service providers to deliver the links that are used in WANs.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] It is also possible to build a WAN with Ethernet.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Academic research into wide area networks can be broken down into three areas: mathematical models, network emulation, and network simulation.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Performance improvements are sometimes delivered via wide area file services or WAN optimization.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Of the approximately four billion addresses defined in IPv4, about 18 million addresses in three ranges are reserved for use in private networks.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Packets addressed in these ranges are not routable on the public Internet; they are ignored by all public routers.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Therefore, private hosts cannot directly communicate with public networks, but require network address translation at a routing gateway for this purpose.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Additionally, encapsulated packets may be encrypted to secure their data.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Many technologies are available for wide-area network links.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Examples include circuit-switched telephone lines, radio wave transmission, and optical fiber.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] New developments have successively increased transmission rates.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] 1960, a 110 bit/s line was normal on the edge of the WAN, while core links of 56 or 64 kbit/s were considered fast.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Today, households are connected to the Internet with dial-up, asymmetric digital subscriber line (ADSL), cable, WiMAX, cellular network or fiber.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] The speeds that people can currently use range from 28.8 kbit/s through a 28K modem over a telephone connection to speeds as high as 100 Gbit/s using 100 Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] The following communication and networking technologies have been used to implement WANs.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] AT&T conducted trials in 2017 for business use of 400-gigabit Ethernet.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Researchers Robert Maher, Alex Alvarado, Domaniç Lavery, and Polina Bayvel of University College London were able to increase networking speeds to 1.125 terabits per second.
[src:metro-ethernet/wide-area-network] Christos Santis, graduate student Scott Steger, Amnon Yariv, Martin and Eileen Summerfield developed a new laser that potentially quadruples transfer speeds with fiber optics.
